We examine the source parameters ofthe 1949 Khait earthquake, Tajikistan. We conclude it was predominantly strike‐slip on a previously unmapped fault at the Pamir‐Tien Shan boundary. The Khait earthquake shows the hazard posed by “cryptic” faults in the continental interiors.

